To show data from Firebase in your react-native app, you'll need to use a library like Firebase SDK or Firebase REST API to connect to your Firebase database and retrieve the data.

Assuming you're using Firebase SDK, you can follow these steps:

1. Install the Firebase SDK and import it into your app:

```javascript
npm install firebase
import firebase from 'firebase';
```

2. Initialize Firebase with your Firebase app credentials:

```javascript
const firebaseConfig = {
  apiKey: "YOUR_API_KEY",
  authDomain: "YOUR_AUTH_DOMAIN",
  databaseURL: "YOUR_DATABASE_URL",
  projectId: "YOUR_PROJECT_ID",
  storageBucket: "YOUR_STORAGE_BUCKET",
  messagingSenderId: "YOUR_MESSAGING_SENDER_ID",
  appId: "YOUR_APP_ID"
};
firebase.initializeApp(firebaseConfig);
```

3. Create a reference to your PastMK collection:

```javascript
const db = firebase.firestore();
const PastMKRef = db.collection('PastMK');
```

4. Retrieve data from the PastMK collection and display it in your component:

```javascript
import { useState, useEffect } from 'react';

export default function PastMK() {
  const navigation = useNavigation();
  const [pastMKList, setPastMKList] = useState([]);

  useEffect(() => {
    let unsub = PastMKRef.onSnapshot((querySnapshot) => {
      let pastMKs = [];
      querySnapshot.forEach((doc) => {
        let data = doc.data();
        pastMKs.push({
          id: doc.id,
          name: data.name,
          image: data.image,
          description: data.description,
          time: data.time
        });
      });
      setPastMKList(pastMKs);
    });
    return unsub;
  }, []);

  return (
    <View style={gStyle.main}>
      {pastMKList.map((pastMK) => (
        <View key={pastMK.id} style={gStyle.PastMKbox}>
          <View style={gStyle.PastMKcontainer}>
            <View style={gStyle.PastMKbox1}>
              <View style={gStyle.PastMKpastImg}>
                <Image
                  source={{ uri: pastMK.image }}
                  style={gStyle.PastMKimg}
                />
                <View style={gStyle.PastMKinfo}>
                  <Text style={gStyle.PastMKnameOfMK}>{pastMK.name}</Text>
                  <Text style={gStyle.PastMKdateOfMK}>{pastMK.time}</Text>
                </View>
              </View>
              <Text style={gStyle.PastMKdescription}>{pastMK.description}</Text>
              <Pressable
                style={gStyle.PastMKreadMore}
                onPress={() =>
                  navigation.navigate('PastMKInfo', { id: pastMK.id })
                }
              >
                <Text style={gStyle.PastMKtxtBtn}>Читать далее</Text>
              </Pressable>
            </View>
          </View>
        </View>
      ))}
      <Text style={gStyle.PastMKline}></Text>
    </View>
  );
}
```

In this example, we're using the `onSnapshot` method to listen for changes to the PastMK collection in real-time. We're creating an array of PastMK objects from the data returned by the query, using the `map` function to render each item in the array as a component.

Note that the `image` property in the PastMK object should be a URL that points to the image asset stored in Firebase Storage, not the actual image data itself. If your image assets are stored in your app's assets folder, you can use the `require` function to load the image data into your component as shown in your original code.

You can create a reference to your PastMK collection anywhere within your Firebase SDK initialization code in your app. Typically, this code would be placed in your App.js or index.js file since these files are typically the entry points to your app.

Here's an example of how you can create a reference to your PastMK collection within your Firebase SDK initialization code:

```javascript
import firebase from 'firebase/app';
import 'firebase/firestore';

// Your Firebase SDK initialization code goes here
const firebaseConfig = { /* Your config options */ };
firebase.initializeApp(firebaseConfig);

// Get a reference to your PastMK collection
